00:02:44.723 --> 00:02:46.390
I will mention, though,
that at the end,

00:02:46.390 --> 00:02:50.940
we came up with our
stopping power expression.

00:02:50.940 --> 00:02:55.500
Let's call this
ionizations that came out

00:02:55.500 --> 00:03:00.360
to 4 pi, this constant
k0 squared, which

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:05.940
comes from the Coulomb force
law, little z squared, big Z, e

00:03:05.940 --> 00:03:11.796
to the 4th over mass of the
electron velocity squared--

00:03:11.796 --> 00:03:13.500
I'm running out of room--

00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:20.730
times log of mass of
the electron v squared

00:03:20.730 --> 00:03:27.680
over this mean
excitation energy, which

00:03:27.680 --> 00:03:29.840
comes out to around,
let's say, 10

00:03:29.840 --> 00:03:34.780
to 19 electron volts times z.

00:03:34.780 --> 00:03:38.320
And what this meant was that
if we graph stopping power

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:47.380
as a function of energy, there's
a couple components to it.

00:03:47.380 --> 00:03:51.400
One of them is this roughly
1 over energy component.

00:03:51.400 --> 00:03:53.550
So let's say there's
a component of it--

00:03:53.550 --> 00:03:55.260
yes, I love when I can do that--

00:03:55.260 --> 00:03:58.260
that actually-- that
follows 1 over e.

00:03:58.260 --> 00:04:04.060
And there's this logarithmic
component that goes that way.

00:04:04.060 --> 00:04:10.350
And if we sum them together,
we ended up with a much higher

00:04:10.350 --> 00:04:11.910
stopping power at low energies.

00:04:11.910 --> 00:04:16.029
But around this local
minimum of about 3 times

00:04:16.029 --> 00:04:18.240
the mass of the
electron c squared,

00:04:18.240 --> 00:04:20.279
it starts to increase again.

00:04:20.279 --> 00:04:22.180
And that's due to this.

00:04:22.180 --> 00:04:25.870
How many excitations can you
make as a function of energy?

00:04:25.870 --> 00:04:29.070
So if you think about it, this
is kind of like an energy term.

00:04:29.070 --> 00:04:32.850
How much energy do you have
divided by how many ionizations

00:04:32.850 --> 00:04:34.380
can you make?

00:04:34.380 --> 00:04:36.853
So it's kind of an intuitive
result in that it's

00:04:36.853 --> 00:04:39.270
how much energy you've got
versus how much energy it takes

00:04:39.270 --> 00:04:41.220
for a single unit process.

00:04:41.220 --> 00:04:44.083
And that's all mediated
by this 1 over e term.

00:04:44.083 --> 00:04:45.750
The last thing that
we said is that this

00:04:45.750 --> 00:04:49.170
curves back down here.

00:04:49.170 --> 00:04:56.320
And that's because at around
500 times this mean excitation

00:04:56.320 --> 00:05:01.280
energy, which as you can see
is around 1 keV times z--

00:05:01.280 --> 00:05:03.250
it's not a very high energy--

00:05:03.250 --> 00:05:06.834
you start to get
charged neutralization.

00:05:12.410 --> 00:05:15.410
The reason for that is that
for-- in order for this formula

00:05:15.410 --> 00:05:19.920
to work, we have to assume
that the deflection is really,

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:23.010
really, really small,
infinitesimally small.

00:05:23.010 --> 00:05:27.560
If it's not, and if the ion
manages to catch that electron,

00:05:27.560 --> 00:05:32.720
it's not going to lose energy
by undergoing a Coulomb

00:05:32.720 --> 00:05:33.283
interaction.

00:05:33.283 --> 00:05:35.450
It's going to lose energy
by absorbing that electron

00:05:35.450 --> 00:05:36.710
and neutralizing.

00:05:36.710 --> 00:05:39.260
And so for really
low energy, the ions

00:05:39.260 --> 00:05:41.200
are moving so slowly
that they can capture

00:05:41.200 --> 00:05:42.200
some of those electrons.

00:05:42.200 --> 00:05:45.560
And it gets less and less
effective at stopping

00:05:45.560 --> 00:05:47.960
the material.

00:05:47.960 --> 00:05:49.190
And this led to--

00:05:49.190 --> 00:05:52.210
let's see-- this,
we're distance,

00:05:52.210 --> 00:05:58.550
and this, we're dt dx
times the energy required

00:05:58.550 --> 00:06:01.980
to make an ion pair, which
we'll just call this i.

00:06:01.980 --> 00:06:07.393
We ended up with a curve that
looked something like this.

00:06:07.393 --> 00:06:08.810
This right here
we call the range.

00:06:11.460 --> 00:06:14.400
We just gave that the symbol r.

00:06:14.400 --> 00:06:15.840
So that's the
review of last time,

00:06:15.840 --> 00:06:18.870
but I left some extra space for
some reasons which will become

00:06:18.870 --> 00:06:22.560
clear in about half an hour.

00:06:22.560 --> 00:06:25.200
Right now I want to take
you through a little bit

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:27.030
of a whirlwind in terms
of Bremsstrahlung.

00:06:27.030 --> 00:06:29.040
I'm not going to derive
anything about it.

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:32.310
We're just going to go over what
the cross-sections and stopping

00:06:32.310 --> 00:06:35.470
powers look like, why they
take that form intuitively.

00:06:35.470 --> 00:06:38.160
But we're not going to go
through a rigorous derivation

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:40.920
because, well, we
simply don't have time.

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:43.350
But I do want you to know
what sort of things exist.

00:06:43.350 --> 00:06:46.786
So for Bremsstrahlung, better
known as braking radiation--

00:06:52.250 --> 00:06:55.170
who's actually heard
of this before?

00:06:55.170 --> 00:06:57.440
Does anyone know roughly--

00:06:57.440 --> 00:07:03.120
let's say if we were to
say some cross-section

00:07:03.120 --> 00:07:04.140
for Bremsstrahlung.

00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:07.290
Let's call it
cross-section radiative.

00:07:07.290 --> 00:07:09.210
Because in this
case, we're actually

00:07:09.210 --> 00:07:12.570
talking about the charged
particle radiating away

00:07:12.570 --> 00:07:13.240
photons.

00:07:13.240 --> 00:07:18.060
So let's say we had some
nucleus of charge big Z,

00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:20.990
and we had some ion--

00:07:20.990 --> 00:07:23.430
we'll look at a
different color--

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:27.950
some ion of charge little
Z moving towards it.

00:07:27.950 --> 00:07:30.330
It will either be
attracted or repelled

00:07:30.330 --> 00:07:32.760
depending on what
the sign looks like.

00:07:32.760 --> 00:07:36.405
And sometimes you might
get radiation of a photon.

00:07:39.150 --> 00:07:44.650
Let's call it of energy
E equals hc over lambda.

00:07:44.650 --> 00:07:47.500
That'll become
important in a sec.

00:07:47.500 --> 00:07:49.688
So this radiative
cross-section--

00:07:51.997 --> 00:07:53.580
I don't care about--
particularly care

00:07:53.580 --> 00:07:56.700
about the exact form, but
what is it proportional to?

00:07:56.700 --> 00:07:58.140
What sort of
factors do you think

00:07:58.140 --> 00:08:02.370
would make the emission of that
photon more or less likely?

00:08:02.370 --> 00:08:03.200
Yeah?

00:08:03.200 --> 00:08:05.320
AUDIENCE: The energy of
the charged particle.

00:08:05.320 --> 00:08:07.528
MIKE SHORT: Sure, the energy
of the charged particle.

00:08:07.528 --> 00:08:09.870
So you can-- there's one
expression I like you.

00:08:09.870 --> 00:08:12.060
Can only take my money
until you take it all.

00:08:12.060 --> 00:08:14.340
Well, the same thing goes
for the energy of a photon.

00:08:14.340 --> 00:08:18.198
You can't radiate any
more than the energy

00:08:18.198 --> 00:08:19.740
of the particle
coming in, so there's

00:08:19.740 --> 00:08:24.760
going to be some
maximum energy which

00:08:24.760 --> 00:08:29.020
is going to correspond to
some minimum wavelength, which

00:08:29.020 --> 00:08:32.380
is-- let's say if we just put
our initial energy in here,

00:08:32.380 --> 00:08:36.090
that gives us our minimum
wavelength right there.

00:08:42.010 --> 00:08:43.179
That's true.

00:08:43.179 --> 00:08:46.810
And it can radiate at any
energy smaller than that

00:08:46.810 --> 00:08:48.700
or any wavelength
larger than that.

00:08:48.700 --> 00:08:50.710
I'm basically saying
the same thing.

00:08:50.710 --> 00:08:53.170
Because if this particle
started off further away

00:08:53.170 --> 00:08:58.450
and felt less of a deflection,
it could still emit a photon,

00:08:58.450 --> 00:09:00.918
but of a longer wavelength.

00:09:00.918 --> 00:09:02.710
Don't have room to draw
enough wavelengths,

00:09:02.710 --> 00:09:05.660
but I want to make sure
that's physically accurate.

00:09:05.660 --> 00:09:07.600
So it's actually going
to be also proportional

00:09:07.600 --> 00:09:10.990
to z of the large nucleus.

00:09:10.990 --> 00:09:14.027
The stronger the pull, the
more of that breaking radiation

00:09:14.027 --> 00:09:14.860
you're going to see.

00:09:14.860 --> 00:09:18.370
It's actually
proportional to z squared.

00:09:18.370 --> 00:09:22.360
What this says is that heavier
z materials produce a lot more

00:09:22.360 --> 00:09:24.560
of this breaking radiation.

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:28.120
And it's also proportional
to the inverse

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:29.950
of the mass squared.

00:09:29.950 --> 00:09:33.220
What this says intuitively is
a heavier particle deflects

00:09:33.220 --> 00:09:37.390
less and emits less of
this breaking radiation.

00:09:37.390 --> 00:09:40.480
Hopefully this makes a
lot of sense to you guys,

00:09:40.480 --> 00:09:42.672
that the stronger the pull
of the nucleus, the more

00:09:42.672 --> 00:09:45.130
deflection you're going to get,
and the more Bremsstrahlung

00:09:45.130 --> 00:09:46.330
you'll get.

00:09:46.330 --> 00:09:48.490
The larger the mass
of the incoming ion--

00:09:48.490 --> 00:09:51.000
let's say that's mass m--

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:54.290
the less deflection you'll
get because the less--

00:09:54.290 --> 00:09:54.790
what is it?

00:09:54.790 --> 00:09:58.270
The less momentum transfer you
can apply with the same force

00:09:58.270 --> 00:10:01.582
if you've got a
heavier particle.

00:10:01.582 --> 00:10:04.040
Does this make
sense to everybody?

00:10:04.040 --> 00:10:11.270
So what this says is it's really
important for high z materials.

00:10:14.208 --> 00:10:15.500
And we'll see a little bit why.

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:19.963
If I actually write the full
expression for stopping power--

00:10:19.963 --> 00:10:21.380
and I promise to
you I'm not going

00:10:21.380 --> 00:10:26.270
to derive it because we don't
really have the time for that.

00:10:26.270 --> 00:10:28.880
It's proportional to
the number density.

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:31.130
You should always think there
will be a number density

00:10:31.130 --> 00:10:33.347
and stopping power, because
the more atoms there are,

00:10:33.347 --> 00:10:34.430
the more they stop things.

00:10:34.430 --> 00:10:36.410
It's just directly proportional.

00:10:36.410 --> 00:10:40.860
Times that kinetic
energy plus mec squared.

00:10:40.860 --> 00:10:43.400
And again, this is not something
I want you to memorize,

00:10:43.400 --> 00:10:44.900
but it is something
I want you to be

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:49.040
able to decompose and explain
why the parts are there.

00:10:49.040 --> 00:10:49.580
Let's see.

00:10:49.580 --> 00:10:56.320
Times some radiative
cross-section

00:10:56.320 --> 00:11:04.550
where this sigma radiative is
some constant cross-section.

00:11:04.550 --> 00:11:12.730
This ends up being about
1/500 barns times z squared

00:11:12.730 --> 00:11:16.570
times this parameter b, which
if you see in the reading

00:11:16.570 --> 00:11:18.340
is actually given just--

00:11:18.340 --> 00:11:22.810
this b scales roughly
with the atomic--

00:11:22.810 --> 00:11:26.500
I'm sorry-- yeah, with the
proton number of the material.

00:11:26.500 --> 00:11:29.500
So you can see that in
here, in the stopping power

00:11:29.500 --> 00:11:32.090
is actually directly
the cross-section.

00:11:32.090 --> 00:11:35.140
So the components of
a stopping power--

00:11:35.140 --> 00:11:44.320
there's going to be some
probability of interaction,

00:11:44.320 --> 00:11:48.190
and there's going to be
some energy transfer part.

00:11:51.680 --> 00:11:53.612
This is an interesting
result to show.

00:11:53.612 --> 00:11:55.820
This is why I wanted to just
write the Bremsstrahlung

00:11:55.820 --> 00:11:57.050
stopping power.

00:11:57.050 --> 00:11:59.360
Because in here, actually,
is the cross-section

00:11:59.360 --> 00:12:01.940
times some other stuff.

00:12:01.940 --> 00:12:04.400
Pretty neat result.
And so now I want

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:06.860
to show you how our
cross-section is actually

00:12:06.860 --> 00:12:10.233
contained in the
ionization stopping power.

00:12:10.233 --> 00:12:11.900
So let's bring this
back down for a sec.

00:12:14.510 --> 00:12:18.080
You can think of the likelihood
that the ion comes off

00:12:18.080 --> 00:12:22.070
with any particular energy
to be directly related

00:12:22.070 --> 00:12:23.810
to this impact parameter.

00:12:23.810 --> 00:12:27.170
Because as we saw, the final
expression for stopping power

00:12:27.170 --> 00:12:30.200
is directly related
to this parameter b.

00:12:30.200 --> 00:12:32.990
We ended up integrating
over all possible b

00:12:32.990 --> 00:12:36.020
to get the total stopping
power in the material.

00:12:36.020 --> 00:12:37.640
But if we didn't
do that integral--

00:12:37.640 --> 00:12:40.940
if we stopped, let's say,
at this stage in the game,

00:12:40.940 --> 00:12:43.610
and we said, all right,
well, the stopping power

00:12:43.610 --> 00:12:49.070
at some fixed b actually
depends on the probability

00:12:49.070 --> 00:12:53.630
that that particle enters into
this cross-sectional area right

00:12:53.630 --> 00:13:00.200
here, this 2 pi b db,
that right there is

00:13:00.200 --> 00:13:02.720
the cross-section for
scattering as a function

00:13:02.720 --> 00:13:06.990
of the incoming energy
and the outgoing energy.

00:13:06.990 --> 00:13:08.740
This is one of the
coolest parts, I think,

00:13:08.740 --> 00:13:10.540
is that there is an
actual area right here.

00:13:10.540 --> 00:13:15.250
It's the area of a hollow circle
is the actual cross-section

00:13:15.250 --> 00:13:18.995
for scattering with a
given ingoing and outgoing,

00:13:18.995 --> 00:13:21.150
outcoming energy.

00:13:21.150 --> 00:13:24.090
And then the rest
of this stuff--

00:13:24.090 --> 00:13:27.210
if you pull all this together,
if you take a microscopic

00:13:27.210 --> 00:13:30.420
cross-section times the number
of particles that are there--

00:13:30.420 --> 00:13:39.720
because this is your
atomic number density,

00:13:39.720 --> 00:13:45.810
and these two together are
your electron number density.

00:13:45.810 --> 00:13:48.000
Like we talked about
before with reaction rates

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:49.800
and cross-sections,
this thing right

00:13:49.800 --> 00:13:54.630
here is your macroscopic
cross-section for an incoming

00:13:54.630 --> 00:13:59.500
and an outgoing energy contained
directly in the stopping power

00:13:59.500 --> 00:14:01.420
formula, because
then we integrated

00:14:01.420 --> 00:14:04.240
over all possible
cross sections, which

00:14:04.240 --> 00:14:07.960
means all possible outgoing
energies for a given

00:14:07.960 --> 00:14:10.270
incoming energy.

00:14:10.270 --> 00:14:13.660
And so the last bit, the way
to link these two together,

00:14:13.660 --> 00:14:17.860
which is why I left a little
bit of space right here--

00:14:17.860 --> 00:14:20.805
we know right now, because
I wrote it up there,

00:14:20.805 --> 00:14:22.180
that the scattering
cross-section

00:14:22.180 --> 00:14:29.890
as a function of the ingoing an
outgoing energy per unit energy

00:14:29.890 --> 00:14:34.555
is just the area of
that hollow circle.

00:14:34.555 --> 00:14:38.500
So let's divide
everything by dt.

00:14:38.500 --> 00:14:41.230
We end up with the total
formula for cross--

00:14:41.230 --> 00:14:44.050
for the scattering
cross-section.

00:14:44.050 --> 00:14:46.970
We don't know what
this b db dt is.

00:14:46.970 --> 00:14:49.810
What's the differential
probability

00:14:49.810 --> 00:14:52.240
between impact parameter
and outgoing energy?

00:14:52.240 --> 00:14:56.020
We don't quite know,
but we can express this

00:14:56.020 --> 00:14:58.930
as a change of variables
that we do know.

00:14:58.930 --> 00:15:04.480
We do know-- if we have a
certain impact parameter,

00:15:04.480 --> 00:15:06.670
we know what the scattering
angle is going to be.

00:15:06.670 --> 00:15:08.860
There is a well-known
relation for that.

00:15:08.860 --> 00:15:11.290
And there's a
derivation in the book

00:15:11.290 --> 00:15:14.290
and in another book that
I want to point out to you

00:15:14.290 --> 00:15:19.810
guys by Gary Was called
Fundamentals of Radiation

00:15:19.810 --> 00:15:27.360
Material Science on page 32.

00:15:27.360 --> 00:15:29.700
If anyone wants to see
the derivation from which

00:15:29.700 --> 00:15:32.940
this result came from,
you can head right there,

00:15:32.940 --> 00:15:35.490
and it's free on MIT Libraries.

00:15:35.490 --> 00:15:39.060
Meanwhile, we do know our
relation between this impact

00:15:39.060 --> 00:15:41.490
parameter and the
angle, and we do

00:15:41.490 --> 00:15:46.855
know a relation between this
angle and the outgoing energy.

00:15:46.855 --> 00:15:49.230
And this is where some of the
hard sphere collision stuff

00:15:49.230 --> 00:15:51.640
comes in.

00:15:51.640 --> 00:15:54.790
What's the maximum
amount of energy

00:15:54.790 --> 00:15:57.580
that a particle can
impart to another particle

00:15:57.580 --> 00:16:01.690
in some sort of a hard,
sphere-like collision?

00:16:01.690 --> 00:16:02.900
Let's take the easy example.

00:16:02.900 --> 00:16:05.680
If the two particles
have equal mass,

00:16:05.680 --> 00:16:09.617
how much energy can one
particle impart to another?

00:16:09.617 --> 00:16:10.450
AUDIENCE: All of it.

00:16:10.450 --> 00:16:11.658
MIKE SHORT: All of it, right?

00:16:11.658 --> 00:16:13.390
It can impart a
maximum of, let's say,

00:16:13.390 --> 00:16:16.150
this incoming energy ei.

00:16:16.150 --> 00:16:21.730
As those mass ratios change,
you can impart a maximum--

00:16:21.730 --> 00:16:25.400
let's say your
maximum becomes what's

00:16:25.400 --> 00:16:30.880
called gamma ei where
this gamma right here

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:35.950
is 4 times those two
masses multiplied

00:16:35.950 --> 00:16:40.360
over the sum squared.

00:16:40.360 --> 00:16:43.240
The full expression-- I'm
going to use a different color

00:16:43.240 --> 00:16:45.010
because I'm running
out of space here.

00:16:45.010 --> 00:16:51.700
The full expression for t is
actually gamma ei over 2 times

00:16:51.700 --> 00:16:57.110
1 minus cosine theta.

00:16:57.110 --> 00:17:03.250
The two intuitive limits from
this is if theta equals pi,

00:17:03.250 --> 00:17:06.940
then this here equals 2,
and t is our t maximum,

00:17:06.940 --> 00:17:09.730
just gamma times ei.

00:17:09.730 --> 00:17:15.510
If theta equals 0, that
whole thing equals 0.

00:17:15.510 --> 00:17:17.910
And in our case of
forward scattering,

00:17:17.910 --> 00:17:22.204
no interaction occurs, and
the energy imparted is 0.

00:17:22.204 --> 00:17:23.579
But the important
part here is we

00:17:23.579 --> 00:17:27.630
have a direct relation
between t and theta

00:17:27.630 --> 00:17:30.750
and the angle, which
we can put in here.

00:17:30.750 --> 00:17:33.643
And we actually have a direct
relation between b and theta,

00:17:33.643 --> 00:17:35.310
which I wrote down
so I wouldn't forget.

00:17:39.510 --> 00:17:41.260
So we actually have--
our impact parameter

00:17:41.260 --> 00:17:44.500
is classical radius
of the electron times

00:17:44.500 --> 00:17:46.795
cosine of angle over 2.

00:17:46.795 --> 00:17:48.670
You don't have to know
where these came from,

00:17:48.670 --> 00:17:50.680
but the point is we have
a relation between B

00:17:50.680 --> 00:17:51.820
and the angle.

00:17:51.820 --> 00:17:54.400
We have a relation
between angle and energy.

00:17:54.400 --> 00:17:56.290
So we can just do a
change of variables

00:17:56.290 --> 00:17:59.233
to get our final cross-section.

00:18:02.410 --> 00:18:06.210
And it ends up being, I think,
pi times radius of the electron

00:18:06.210 --> 00:18:08.715
squared over gamma.

00:18:11.220 --> 00:18:14.220
So in this way, we can go from
known relations between each

00:18:14.220 --> 00:18:18.120
of the variables and an
actual physical cross-section

00:18:18.120 --> 00:18:24.240
that has units of real area
down to an energy-dependent form

00:18:24.240 --> 00:18:27.485
for this cross-section,
which I think is pretty cool.

00:18:27.485 --> 00:18:28.860
And then this is
the one that you

00:18:28.860 --> 00:18:31.440
would see tabulated
in the JANIS tables,

00:18:31.440 --> 00:18:34.590
like the energy-dependent
cross-section for the S

00:18:34.590 --> 00:18:36.995
reaction or the scattering.

00:18:36.995 --> 00:18:39.120
So this is one of my favorite
parts of this course,

00:18:39.120 --> 00:18:42.360
because you can see how
cross-sections really

00:18:42.360 --> 00:18:46.290
do follow directly from areas.

00:18:46.290 --> 00:18:49.870
So now for the other
part, now that we've

00:18:49.870 --> 00:18:53.880
got this Bremsstrahlung
stopping power

00:18:53.880 --> 00:18:56.460
and we've got our
ionization stopping power,

00:18:56.460 --> 00:18:59.970
it's useful to find out which
one is more important when.

00:18:59.970 --> 00:19:02.550
To do that, we just
look at their ratios.

00:19:02.550 --> 00:19:13.180
So if we look at the dt dx
from ionizations over the dx dx

00:19:13.180 --> 00:19:17.980
from radiative energy
transfer or Bremsstrahlung--

00:19:17.980 --> 00:19:20.020
let me make sure I
get this one right.

00:19:20.020 --> 00:19:26.540
It's proportional to z times
mass of the electron over m

00:19:26.540 --> 00:19:35.760
squared times t over 1,400
rest mass of the electron.

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:38.200
So what this tells
you here is that--

00:19:38.200 --> 00:19:38.700
I'm sorry.

00:19:38.700 --> 00:19:41.910
I think I have those
backwards, because radiative

00:19:41.910 --> 00:19:45.545
should get more important
at higher energies.

00:19:49.790 --> 00:19:52.550
So what this tells you is
for higher z materials,

00:19:52.550 --> 00:19:54.790
Bremsstrahlung
becomes more dominant,

00:19:54.790 --> 00:19:56.830
and for higher
energies, Bremsstrahlung

00:19:56.830 --> 00:19:59.270
becomes more dominant.

00:19:59.270 --> 00:20:04.460
So if we want to generalize our
stopping power curve from just

00:20:04.460 --> 00:20:07.580
ionization to everything--

00:20:07.580 --> 00:20:09.200
so I know I had another color.

00:20:09.200 --> 00:20:09.700
No.

00:20:09.700 --> 00:20:10.857
I ran out of colors.

00:20:10.857 --> 00:20:11.690
I need a fourth one.

00:20:15.500 --> 00:20:19.520
There's going to be some
Bremsstrahlung component that

00:20:19.520 --> 00:20:21.380
starts to get more
and more important

00:20:21.380 --> 00:20:23.300
with increasing energy.

00:20:23.300 --> 00:20:26.203
And so then if you
extend this curve,

00:20:26.203 --> 00:20:28.370
you're going to radiate
more and more and more power

00:20:28.370 --> 00:20:30.110
the higher energy you go--

00:20:30.110 --> 00:20:35.790
not from this component or
that component of ionization,

00:20:35.790 --> 00:20:39.060
but from radiation
or Bremsstrahlung.

00:20:39.060 --> 00:20:42.180
So this has some pretty
serious implications

00:20:42.180 --> 00:20:46.335
to answer questions like,
how do you shield beta rays?

00:20:46.335 --> 00:20:48.230
Does anyone have any idea?

00:20:48.230 --> 00:20:50.900
Based on this
formula right here,

00:20:50.900 --> 00:20:53.240
what would you use to
shield beta particles

00:20:53.240 --> 00:20:56.780
and not irradiate the person
standing behind the shield?

00:21:01.150 --> 00:21:02.650
Let's ask a question
everyone knows.

00:21:02.650 --> 00:21:06.550
What do you use to shield
photons really well?

00:21:06.550 --> 00:21:10.090
Lead, tungsten,
something with high z.

00:21:10.090 --> 00:21:11.425
Because as we saw from before--

00:21:11.425 --> 00:21:15.160
I'm going to steal a little
bit of the Rutherford stuff.

00:21:15.160 --> 00:21:19.870
If you graph the energy
versus the mass attenuation

00:21:19.870 --> 00:21:25.120
coefficient, you get a
curve that looks like this,

00:21:25.120 --> 00:21:29.920
but everything increases
with increasing z.

00:21:29.920 --> 00:21:32.260
You get more mass attenuation
with increasing z.

00:21:32.260 --> 00:21:35.470
And also, denser materials
tend to be higher z.

00:21:35.470 --> 00:21:37.960
Is that what you want to
do for beta particles?

00:21:40.667 --> 00:21:42.250
You say-- so Monica,
you're saying no.

00:21:42.250 --> 00:21:42.903
How come?

00:21:42.903 --> 00:21:44.528
AUDIENCE: Don't you
just want something

00:21:44.528 --> 00:21:46.858
with a low cross-section?

00:21:46.858 --> 00:21:47.900
MIKE SHORT: That's right.

00:21:47.900 --> 00:21:50.120
Well, you don't
necessarily want something

00:21:50.120 --> 00:21:51.620
with a low
cross-section, or else it

00:21:51.620 --> 00:21:54.415
might not shield at all, but
you are on the right track.

00:21:54.415 --> 00:21:56.040
You can actually look
at the difference

00:21:56.040 --> 00:21:58.973
between these stopping
powers, and cross-sections

00:21:58.973 --> 00:21:59.890
are embedded in there.

00:21:59.890 --> 00:22:02.200
So I think that answer
is pretty much correct.

00:22:02.200 --> 00:22:04.870
But also, you're going to
get more Bremsstrahlung

00:22:04.870 --> 00:22:08.150
or more breaking radiation
in higher z materials.

00:22:08.150 --> 00:22:10.990
So if we actually look at what
thresholds does this become

00:22:10.990 --> 00:22:21.490
important in lead, this ratio
is about 1 at around 10 MeV,

00:22:21.490 --> 00:22:23.710
which means that you lose
an equal amount of energy

00:22:23.710 --> 00:22:28.930
to Bremsstrahlung as ionization
at 10 MeV for electrons.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:41.370
In water, this ratio
is about 1 at 100 MeV.

00:22:41.370 --> 00:22:45.640
So what this says is if you
want to shield electrons or beta

00:22:45.640 --> 00:22:47.400
particles safely,
you actually have

00:22:47.400 --> 00:22:49.560
to use lower Z
materials because they

00:22:49.560 --> 00:22:51.360
won't make much Bremsstrahlung.

00:22:51.360 --> 00:22:53.910
But because, like Monica
said, then the cross-section

00:22:53.910 --> 00:22:56.780
is lower, you actually
have to use more.

00:22:56.780 --> 00:22:58.300
So you don't have a choice.

00:22:58.300 --> 00:23:01.950
You can't just use
less high z material.

00:23:01.950 --> 00:23:04.410
Because while you will
stop more of the electrons,

00:23:04.410 --> 00:23:07.110
they will create more
x-rays in the process.

00:23:07.110 --> 00:23:09.630
And those x-rays are
highly penetrating,

00:23:09.630 --> 00:23:12.480
as we know from these
mass attenuation curves.

00:23:12.480 --> 00:23:14.880
Once you get to high
energy, this is--

00:23:14.880 --> 00:23:16.440
these are logarithmic
scales, so let

00:23:16.440 --> 00:23:22.190
me correct those and
say these are log of e

00:23:22.190 --> 00:23:24.030
and log of mu over p.

00:23:24.030 --> 00:23:26.580
It gets millions of
times less effective

00:23:26.580 --> 00:23:30.630
at shielding high
energy photons.

00:23:30.630 --> 00:23:32.880
So that's one of those really
important things to note

00:23:32.880 --> 00:23:34.838
is if you're designing
shielding for something,

00:23:34.838 --> 00:23:38.440
and there are electrons involved
that are even around 1 MeV

00:23:38.440 --> 00:23:42.460
or so, you can't just use high
z materials to shield them,

00:23:42.460 --> 00:23:46.490
or you will create more
problems than you solve.

00:23:46.490 --> 00:23:48.350
That's a pretty
important implication.

00:23:48.350 --> 00:23:52.757
It's quite important for what's
called betavoltaic devices.

00:23:52.757 --> 00:23:54.340
It's kind of a
sidetrack, so I'm going

00:23:54.340 --> 00:23:57.380
to stick it on a board
that'll be hidden soon.

00:23:57.380 --> 00:23:59.205
Has anyone heard of
a betavoltaic device?

00:24:02.630 --> 00:24:03.770
Anyone?

00:24:03.770 --> 00:24:05.286
What are they?

00:24:05.286 --> 00:24:06.770
AUDIENCE: It's
like a beta source

00:24:06.770 --> 00:24:11.320
that emits electrons onto a
semiconductor [INAUDIBLE]..

00:24:11.320 --> 00:24:13.110
MIKE SHORT: Yeah,
it's a beta battery.

00:24:13.110 --> 00:24:19.940
All it is is, let's say,
some pieces of silicon,

00:24:19.940 --> 00:24:26.060
some circuit that grabs the
power, and a beta emitter.

00:24:26.060 --> 00:24:29.300
And these beta particles
directly hit the silicon,

00:24:29.300 --> 00:24:32.930
and the movement of those
betas constitutes a charge.

00:24:32.930 --> 00:24:36.680
And it's direct-- it's direct
conversion of radiation

00:24:36.680 --> 00:24:38.240
to electrical energy.

00:24:38.240 --> 00:24:42.180
They're not very high power, but
they last for a very long time.

00:24:42.180 --> 00:24:43.430
How long?

00:24:43.430 --> 00:24:46.515
Around a few half lives
of that beta decay.

00:24:46.515 --> 00:24:48.140
So for most of these
beta emitters that

00:24:48.140 --> 00:24:51.530
have half lives in the realm
of, like, 10 to 1,000 years,

00:24:51.530 --> 00:24:55.490
you can make a microwatt battery
that could last for millennia.

00:24:55.490 --> 00:24:57.320
This could be pretty useful.

00:24:57.320 --> 00:24:59.810
Let's say if you wanted to
have some secret sensors

00:24:59.810 --> 00:25:02.570
in a naughty country
like North Korea,

00:25:02.570 --> 00:25:05.060
you could drop these tiny
little beta particles that would

00:25:05.060 --> 00:25:09.330
just-- betavoltaics that would
just trickle charge a battery,

00:25:09.330 --> 00:25:10.310
make a measurement of--

00:25:10.310 --> 00:25:13.430
I don't know-- radiation level,
or weight of the dictator,

00:25:13.430 --> 00:25:16.010
or whatever you happen
to want to measure,

00:25:16.010 --> 00:25:19.160
and send that off once
a month or once a year

00:25:19.160 --> 00:25:21.620
with no need for
external monitoring.

00:25:21.620 --> 00:25:25.280
Or let's say you're designing
a mission to land on a comet,

00:25:25.280 --> 00:25:29.420
like the Rosetta Philae Lander,
and your radiothermal isotope

00:25:29.420 --> 00:25:32.180
generator is going to burn out
in, let's say, 10 or 20 years.

00:25:32.180 --> 00:25:33.890
You might not need
that much power just

00:25:33.890 --> 00:25:35.600
to measure temperature,
or light levels,

00:25:35.600 --> 00:25:37.370
or something else, or
a gas that you might

00:25:37.370 --> 00:25:39.280
want to know what's there.

00:25:39.280 --> 00:25:42.765
But you have to choose
your beta isotope wisely.

00:25:42.765 --> 00:25:44.890
If you want to make these
things in a little chip--

00:25:44.890 --> 00:25:47.890
and they actually have been
commercialized in a chip

00:25:47.890 --> 00:25:50.470
that's about that
actual size using

00:25:50.470 --> 00:25:53.160
about two curies of tritium.

00:25:53.160 --> 00:25:55.425
Anyone have any idea why
one would choose tritium?

00:26:01.178 --> 00:26:02.720
AUDIENCE: It's got
a short half-life.

00:26:02.720 --> 00:26:03.860
MIKE SHORT: Yeah, it's
got a short half-life,

00:26:03.860 --> 00:26:06.080
so you can get a lot
of power out of it.

00:26:06.080 --> 00:26:08.210
That's one of the
two correct reasons.

00:26:08.210 --> 00:26:10.210
And what is the other one?

00:26:10.210 --> 00:26:14.960
Lets see who's memorized
there KAERI table of nuclides.

00:26:14.960 --> 00:26:17.000
What do you think
its beta decay energy

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:20.549
would have to be for this not
to blast anyone in the vicinity?

00:26:24.461 --> 00:26:25.165
AUDIENCE: Low.

00:26:25.165 --> 00:26:26.040
MIKE SHORT: Very low.

00:26:26.040 --> 00:26:28.210
Why do you say that?

00:26:28.210 --> 00:26:33.540
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] they
don't penetrate all the way

00:26:33.540 --> 00:26:34.540
through the [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:34.540 --> 00:26:35.540
MIKE SHORT: That's true.

00:26:35.540 --> 00:26:37.120
Their range is much smaller.

00:26:37.120 --> 00:26:40.320
But the range of all betas
is pretty low in materials.

00:26:40.320 --> 00:26:43.030
But the answer lies right here--

00:26:43.030 --> 00:26:44.800
less Bremsstrahlung.

00:26:44.800 --> 00:26:48.250
Lower energy betas give
most of their energy

00:26:48.250 --> 00:26:53.020
off in ionization rather than
by radiating Bremsstrahlung.

00:26:53.020 --> 00:26:56.060
So you can have a device
with two curies of tritium,

00:26:56.060 --> 00:26:59.590
which if that's released to the
outside world, that's bad news.

00:26:59.590 --> 00:27:01.990
That's something that
you might have to report.

00:27:01.990 --> 00:27:05.180
But as long as it stays
contained in this device,

00:27:05.180 --> 00:27:08.710
it does not have enough
energy to produce many x-rays

00:27:08.710 --> 00:27:10.030
from Bremsstrahlung.

00:27:10.030 --> 00:27:12.430
And therefore, it does not
require an enormous amount

00:27:12.430 --> 00:27:13.420
of shielding.

00:27:13.420 --> 00:27:15.120
So you can't just
pick a 1 MeV beta

00:27:15.120 --> 00:27:16.870
emitter which you might
get a lot of power

00:27:16.870 --> 00:27:19.420
out of, because it's also
going to be a big, crazy X-ray

00:27:19.420 --> 00:27:22.480
source that you wouldn't want
in a cell phone or a sensor

00:27:22.480 --> 00:27:25.000
or some other device you
might put in your pocket,

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:28.402
or even 20 feet from you.

00:27:28.402 --> 00:27:30.220
Cool.

00:27:30.220 --> 00:27:33.385
So that's the idea
behind Bremsstrahlung.

00:27:33.385 --> 00:27:35.510
There's a little bit more
I want to tell you about,

00:27:35.510 --> 00:27:39.020
and I'll save that for
the sidetrack board.

00:27:39.020 --> 00:27:41.420
We use Bremsstrahlung in a
lot of really interesting

00:27:41.420 --> 00:27:47.000
applications, including
cyclotron, one of which

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:50.990
we just took delivery of here
at MIT, or a synchrotron.

00:27:54.970 --> 00:27:57.470
And I'll just briefly
explain how these work.

00:27:57.470 --> 00:28:01.070
In a cyclotron, you've
got two D-shaped magnets.

00:28:01.070 --> 00:28:04.580
They actually call
them dees because we're

00:28:04.580 --> 00:28:07.520
so creative in
naming these things.

00:28:07.520 --> 00:28:11.890
You inject some source
of charged particles,

00:28:11.890 --> 00:28:19.130
and there is some electric
field lines across these two dee

00:28:19.130 --> 00:28:20.180
magnets.

00:28:20.180 --> 00:28:23.510
And what this says is that
in between the magnets,

00:28:23.510 --> 00:28:25.280
the particle accelerates.

00:28:25.280 --> 00:28:29.180
And inside each magnet,
the path curves.

00:28:29.180 --> 00:28:31.190
And it accelerates some more.

00:28:31.190 --> 00:28:34.420
And it's moving even faster,
so it takes longer to curve.

00:28:34.420 --> 00:28:37.520
Than it moves even faster,
and it takes longer to curve,

00:28:37.520 --> 00:28:44.920
and so on and so on, until it
finally shoots out the side.

00:28:44.920 --> 00:28:47.830
And so this is one way that you
can have an extremely compact--

00:28:47.830 --> 00:28:50.320
and I'm talking like
garbage-can-sized--

00:28:50.320 --> 00:28:54.490
accelerator that brings
things up to about 13 MeV.

00:28:54.490 --> 00:28:57.370
That's the one that we've got
in the basement of Northwest 13.

00:28:57.370 --> 00:28:59.710
The problem is every
time these particles

00:28:59.710 --> 00:29:07.260
bend, they send
off photons, what's

00:29:07.260 --> 00:29:09.240
known as cyclotron radiation.

00:29:09.240 --> 00:29:12.690
And the higher energy
that is, the more intense

00:29:12.690 --> 00:29:14.850
that cyclotron radiation gets.

00:29:14.850 --> 00:29:18.480
So you've got this
garbage-can-sized device with

00:29:18.480 --> 00:29:23.040
a little hole right here, and
it's just blasting out photons

00:29:23.040 --> 00:29:25.140
in all directions
in this one plane--

00:29:25.140 --> 00:29:27.120
let's just call it
the plane of death--

00:29:27.120 --> 00:29:28.770
which you don't
want to be in, which

00:29:28.770 --> 00:29:31.860
is why this the thing is behind
4 feet of concrete shielding,

00:29:31.860 --> 00:29:34.110
and in the middle
of a room, to help--

00:29:34.110 --> 00:29:37.080
that 1 over r squared
keeps your dose down.

00:29:37.080 --> 00:29:42.330
But we actually use this plane
of death in a synchrotron.

00:29:42.330 --> 00:29:44.680
What it is is it's a
circular accelerator.

00:29:44.680 --> 00:29:47.280
It's not quite circular,
so let me correct

00:29:47.280 --> 00:29:48.870
my drawing a little bit.

00:29:48.870 --> 00:29:51.780
There are straight segments,
and there are slightly

00:29:51.780 --> 00:29:52.650
curved segments.

00:29:56.670 --> 00:29:59.490
But it pretty much
looks like a circle

00:29:59.490 --> 00:30:01.200
if you look at it
from high up enough.

00:30:01.200 --> 00:30:04.200
In each of these
curved segments,

00:30:04.200 --> 00:30:05.520
there is a bending magnet.

00:30:08.610 --> 00:30:10.300
That's my best
drawing for a magnet.

00:30:13.110 --> 00:30:15.960
And what this does
is it continuously

00:30:15.960 --> 00:30:21.480
changes the path of these
charged particles going through

00:30:21.480 --> 00:30:23.010
usually electrons.

00:30:23.010 --> 00:30:25.410
And you end up
with intense beams.

00:30:25.410 --> 00:30:26.910
Let me use a different color.

00:30:26.910 --> 00:30:30.690
You end up with intense
beams perpendicular

00:30:30.690 --> 00:30:34.650
to the original path before
it went in that bending magnet

00:30:34.650 --> 00:30:38.700
of synchrotron radiation.

00:30:38.700 --> 00:30:42.420
So it's kind of like
a gigaelectron volt

00:30:42.420 --> 00:30:44.790
spinning ninja star of
death, except at the end

00:30:44.790 --> 00:30:47.700
of every one of these
stations, you have

00:30:47.700 --> 00:30:50.780
what's called a beam line.

00:30:50.780 --> 00:30:55.040
Because there's 60 or
80-odd of these beam lines

00:30:55.040 --> 00:30:56.930
coming off with,
let's say, 80 kv

00:30:56.930 --> 00:30:59.720
and below Bremsstrahlung
x-rays, you

00:30:59.720 --> 00:31:02.760
can use those for a whole lot of
different analysis techniques.

00:31:02.760 --> 00:31:04.820
You can simply irradiate things.

00:31:04.820 --> 00:31:09.140
You can send those x-rays
through a monochromator

00:31:09.140 --> 00:31:12.260
to select only one wavelength,
and then use that wavelength

00:31:12.260 --> 00:31:15.310
to probe the structure of
matter down to the atomic level.

00:31:15.310 --> 00:31:17.810
There's actually one of these
just down in Long Island.

00:31:17.810 --> 00:31:19.490
About a 2-and-1/2-hour
drive from here,

00:31:19.490 --> 00:31:21.530
there's Brookhaven National Lab.

00:31:21.530 --> 00:31:23.780
And they just opened up the
National Synchrotron Light

00:31:23.780 --> 00:31:27.260
Source, or NSLS version
2, where they can actually

00:31:27.260 --> 00:31:32.150
measure distances with
single nanometer precision.

00:31:32.150 --> 00:31:35.840
So inside this beam
line is a bigger room

00:31:35.840 --> 00:31:37.850
which is encased in
another room which

00:31:37.850 --> 00:31:39.710
is encased in another room.

00:31:39.710 --> 00:31:42.230
And the whole point of that is
for vibration and temperature

00:31:42.230 --> 00:31:43.280
isolation.

00:31:43.280 --> 00:31:45.540
So they maintain
this entire room

00:31:45.540 --> 00:31:49.400
to within a speck
of 0.1 Celsius.

00:31:49.400 --> 00:31:52.375
And it's the least vibrating
place, probably, in the US.

00:31:52.375 --> 00:31:53.750
I don't know about
on the planet.

00:31:53.750 --> 00:31:56.750
But it's got basically
no vibration.

00:31:56.750 --> 00:31:58.550
So the atoms are
effectively standing

00:31:58.550 --> 00:32:01.860
still except for their normal
vibrations in the material.

00:32:01.860 --> 00:32:04.017
But there's no source
of external vibration.

00:32:04.017 --> 00:32:05.600
And the cooling has
to come in through

00:32:05.600 --> 00:32:09.500
these convoluted channels so
as not to blow on the sample,

00:32:09.500 --> 00:32:12.450
so as not to make any convection
currents or temperature

00:32:12.450 --> 00:32:12.950
changes.

00:32:12.950 --> 00:32:15.075
And they can actually probe
the structure of matter

00:32:15.075 --> 00:32:19.370
with single-nanometer precision
using these synchrotron x-rays

00:32:19.370 --> 00:32:23.240
all produced by Bremsstrahlung.

00:32:23.240 --> 00:32:24.360
So it's not all bad.

00:32:24.360 --> 00:32:27.535
You can use
Bremsstrahlung for good.

00:32:27.535 --> 00:32:28.660
Then there's a little bit--

00:32:28.660 --> 00:32:30.790
I have to hijack
a little more area

00:32:30.790 --> 00:32:32.805
from Rutherford scattering.

00:32:32.805 --> 00:32:34.180
You might think
about, well, what

00:32:34.180 --> 00:32:37.300
is the actual spectrum
of this Bremsstrahlung.

00:32:37.300 --> 00:32:39.610
Well, you can look to see
what's the probability

00:32:39.610 --> 00:32:45.580
that an atom enters into any
of these concentric, hollow

00:32:45.580 --> 00:32:46.870
circles.

00:32:46.870 --> 00:32:49.510
It looks to be less and
less likely that you're

00:32:49.510 --> 00:32:51.520
going to enter through
one of the center rings

00:32:51.520 --> 00:32:53.020
and more and more
likely that you're

00:32:53.020 --> 00:32:55.190
going to enter through
one of the outer rings.

00:32:55.190 --> 00:32:58.600
If you start farther away,
there's less of a pull

00:32:58.600 --> 00:33:01.180
to change the path of
that ion or electron,

00:33:01.180 --> 00:33:05.000
and the Bremsstrahlung is
going to be lower in energy.

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:06.580
This is actually
described by what's

00:33:06.580 --> 00:33:15.618
called Cramer's law, which
says that the intensity

00:33:15.618 --> 00:33:17.660
of the Bremsstrahlung as
a function of wavelength

00:33:17.660 --> 00:33:21.890
scales with some constant k,
and that constant scales with--

00:33:21.890 --> 00:33:23.900
surprise, surprise--
the atomic number

00:33:23.900 --> 00:33:29.240
of the material
times some lambda

00:33:29.240 --> 00:33:36.273
over lambda minimum minus 1
times 1 over lambda squared.

00:33:36.273 --> 00:33:37.690
And what this says
is that there's

00:33:37.690 --> 00:33:43.110
some minimum lambda
or some maximum energy

00:33:43.110 --> 00:33:45.330
that you can impart to
this Bremsstrahlung, which

00:33:45.330 --> 00:33:48.610
again, you can only take some
energy before you take it all.

00:33:48.610 --> 00:33:52.440
And there's going to be some
sort of a fixed minimum lambda

00:33:52.440 --> 00:33:54.840
if we draw this intensity.

00:33:54.840 --> 00:33:57.120
And I graphed this on Desmos
just before coming here,

00:33:57.120 --> 00:34:00.390
so I know it looks something
like this where that

00:34:00.390 --> 00:34:05.190
right there is lambda minimum.

00:34:05.190 --> 00:34:06.910
It's taking more area.

00:34:06.910 --> 00:34:14.190
If you then change variables
from lambda to the angular

00:34:14.190 --> 00:34:16.110
frequency where,
if you remember,

00:34:16.110 --> 00:34:22.830
the energy of the photon is just
h bar times that frequency-- so

00:34:22.830 --> 00:34:27.420
it's kind of like converting
into energy with just a tiny,

00:34:27.420 --> 00:34:28.679
little constant in front.

00:34:28.679 --> 00:34:31.170
And I mean really, really
tiny little constant.

00:34:31.170 --> 00:34:35.370
You end up with
an energy relation

00:34:35.370 --> 00:34:40.719
that looks like some
maximum angular frequency

00:34:40.719 --> 00:34:44.380
or some maximum energy.

00:34:44.380 --> 00:34:47.909
And this is kind of a simple,
linear-looking relation, this 1

00:34:47.909 --> 00:34:52.000
over energy relation minus 1.

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:54.760
So if we graph energy
versus the intensity

00:34:54.760 --> 00:34:56.679
of the Bremsstrahlung,
you end up

00:34:56.679 --> 00:35:02.170
with a curve something
like this where

00:35:02.170 --> 00:35:07.960
your max energy is the same as
your incoming particle energy.

