00:37:15.210 --> 00:37:17.790
And there's got
to be some window.

00:37:17.790 --> 00:37:20.560
We can make it as thin
as we possibly can.

00:37:20.560 --> 00:37:23.910
And they make it out of the most
X-ray-transparent structural

00:37:23.910 --> 00:37:27.720
material that they can,
which tends to be beryllium.

00:37:27.720 --> 00:37:31.460
So beryllium has got
an atomic number 4.

00:37:31.460 --> 00:37:33.470
It's the first and
lightest element

00:37:33.470 --> 00:37:36.230
that you can make
structural anythings out of.

00:37:36.230 --> 00:37:39.830
So if you want to protect
your detector from, let's say,

00:37:39.830 --> 00:37:41.945
air or something-- if
this were full of air,

00:37:41.945 --> 00:37:43.820
it would absorb the
x-rays, so you want there

00:37:43.820 --> 00:37:45.680
to be pretty much nothing.

00:37:45.680 --> 00:37:50.030
You can put a very thin,
seven-micron beryllium

00:37:50.030 --> 00:37:51.440
window in front.

00:37:51.440 --> 00:37:53.520
But the problem is
we've already got

00:37:53.520 --> 00:37:55.100
one of these mass
attenuation curves.

00:37:55.100 --> 00:37:57.980
And when you get down
to these energy levels,

00:37:57.980 --> 00:37:59.990
you attenuate everything.

00:37:59.990 --> 00:38:03.175
So the lower energy
your Bremsstrahlung is,

00:38:03.175 --> 00:38:04.800
the less likely you're
going to see it.

00:38:04.800 --> 00:38:14.560
So even though this is the
actual Bremsstrahlung spectrum,

00:38:14.560 --> 00:38:15.560
this is what we observe.

00:38:20.040 --> 00:38:22.070
