00:38:26.720 --> 00:38:28.790
in for elemental analysis.

00:38:28.790 --> 00:38:31.640
This is precisely what
we're going to see.

00:38:31.640 --> 00:38:35.000
You're going to see this
Bremsstrahlung which is not

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:37.640
the actual spectrum
coming out, but this

00:38:37.640 --> 00:38:39.530
has to do with the
absorption of x-rays

00:38:39.530 --> 00:38:43.910
in the detector window, as
well as some self-shielding.

00:38:43.910 --> 00:38:46.430
If we're using a scanning
electron microscope, which

00:38:46.430 --> 00:38:49.760
is nothing more than
an electron gun,

00:38:49.760 --> 00:38:53.060
and you're firing electrons to
some distance in the material

00:38:53.060 --> 00:38:59.540
where they'll then interact
and send off x-rays,

00:38:59.540 --> 00:39:03.830
you've also got this part of
the material to contend with,

00:39:03.830 --> 00:39:05.300
some self-shielding.

00:39:07.850 --> 00:39:10.310
So not only do the x-rays
all have to get through

00:39:10.310 --> 00:39:12.680
the detector window
to be counted--

00:39:12.680 --> 00:39:15.560
so the high-energy
ones, which we'll

00:39:15.560 --> 00:39:17.640
have with small
wavelength, get through,

00:39:17.640 --> 00:39:20.090
but the low-energy or
long-wavelength ones

00:39:20.090 --> 00:39:21.530
might get stopped.

00:39:21.530 --> 00:39:24.020
You also have to get out
of the material itself.

00:39:24.020 --> 00:39:25.910
The electrons don't
just produce x-rays

00:39:25.910 --> 00:39:28.130
in the outer atoms
of the material.

00:39:28.130 --> 00:39:30.050
They go down a micron or two.

00:39:30.050 --> 00:39:33.680
And then the x-rays that are
produced in those interactions

00:39:33.680 --> 00:39:36.827
have to get back out again.

00:39:36.827 --> 00:39:37.660
So it's interesting.

00:39:37.660 --> 00:39:40.520
It's kind of like the inverse
photoelectric effect, right?

00:39:40.520 --> 00:39:43.140
In the photoelectric
effect, photon comes in,

00:39:43.140 --> 00:39:44.850
electrons come out.

00:39:44.850 --> 00:39:47.910
In a scanning electron
microscope, electrons come in.

00:39:47.910 --> 00:39:49.380
Photons come out.

00:39:49.380 --> 00:39:53.010
Many of them are these
characteristic x-rays.

00:39:53.010 --> 00:39:54.810
Because now if we
start to review

00:39:54.810 --> 00:39:58.230
what sort of interactions are
possible when we fire electrons

00:39:58.230 --> 00:40:01.465
into material, we've just
gone over Bremsstrahlung.

00:40:01.465 --> 00:40:03.840
And we know that with higher
and higher energy electrons,

00:40:03.840 --> 00:40:05.910
you're going to get more
and more Bremsstrahlung.

00:40:05.910 --> 00:40:09.300
But you're not going to see
the actual x-rays produced

00:40:09.300 --> 00:40:12.810
at low energies no matter
what, because this isn't just

00:40:12.810 --> 00:40:13.710
a system on paper.

00:40:13.710 --> 00:40:15.210
It's real life.

00:40:15.210 --> 00:40:19.140
And you're going to get
characteristic x-rays that

00:40:19.140 --> 00:40:23.220
come from energy transitions.

00:40:23.220 --> 00:40:25.380
So if you fire in
an electron, and you

00:40:25.380 --> 00:40:29.910
happen to undergo one of
these ionization collisions,

00:40:29.910 --> 00:40:33.375
you might just knock
an electron out.

00:40:33.375 --> 00:40:38.250
So let's say an electron comes
in, knocks an electron out.

00:40:38.250 --> 00:40:43.610
Then another electron
fills that shell,

00:40:43.610 --> 00:40:47.840
giving off-- in this case, it
would be a k alpha or a shell 2

00:40:47.840 --> 00:40:50.150
to a shell 1 X-ray
the way I've drawn

00:40:50.150 --> 00:40:52.490
it, which is why Julia
has got everything

00:40:52.490 --> 00:40:54.050
right on the spectrum here.

00:40:54.050 --> 00:40:56.120
There's the Bremsstrahlung,
and then there's

00:40:56.120 --> 00:40:58.460
these characteristic peaks.

00:40:58.460 --> 00:41:01.740
The background is due to
radiative stopping power,

00:41:01.740 --> 00:41:03.500
and these characteristic
peaks give away

00:41:03.500 --> 00:41:06.980
some of the ionization
stopping power.

00:41:06.980 --> 00:41:10.310
And so all in one spectrum, you
can see just about everything

00:41:10.310 --> 00:41:12.930
going on in this material.

00:41:12.930 --> 00:41:17.150
The last thing that you can't
see that I would be remiss

00:41:17.150 --> 00:41:21.860
if I didn't talk about it as
a radiation material scientist

00:41:21.860 --> 00:41:24.590
is radiation material
science, which

00:41:24.590 --> 00:41:29.090
really is concerned with
mostly Rutherford scattering,

00:41:29.090 --> 00:41:31.547
Rutherford or hard
sphere scattering.

00:41:37.760 --> 00:41:41.420
This is the last of
the major interactions

00:41:41.420 --> 00:41:45.230
between charged particles
and matter that concern us.

00:41:45.230 --> 00:41:47.630
It's not really in your
reading except for, I think,

00:41:47.630 --> 00:41:51.282
being mentioned once,
because they didn't

00:41:51.282 --> 00:41:52.490
seem to think it's important.

00:41:52.490 --> 00:41:54.620
But I happen to think
it's extremely important,

00:41:54.620 --> 00:41:56.960
because this is the basis
behind radiation damage.

00:42:03.400 --> 00:42:05.200
In all of these
collisions right here,

00:42:05.200 --> 00:42:08.320
you have some sort of
displacement of electrons.

00:42:08.320 --> 00:42:09.872
And those electrons
can get ionized,

00:42:09.872 --> 00:42:11.830
and other ones will fill
them back in the holes

00:42:11.830 --> 00:42:13.250
and whatever they'll do.

00:42:13.250 --> 00:42:17.200
But at no point were
nuclei displaced.

00:42:17.200 --> 00:42:20.770
You can transfer a lot of
energy without moving any atoms

00:42:20.770 --> 00:42:21.760
around.

00:42:21.760 --> 00:42:24.580
But when your energy
starts to get lower,

00:42:24.580 --> 00:42:29.097
you end up with a new
kind of stopping power--

00:42:29.097 --> 00:42:30.055
let's call it nuclear--

00:42:32.810 --> 00:42:39.350
which scales with, as always,
a number density times pi.

00:42:39.350 --> 00:42:40.640
Let's see.

00:42:40.640 --> 00:42:42.740
Little z, big z, e the 4th--

00:42:42.740 --> 00:42:46.310
everything looks pretty
similar so far, except for now

00:42:46.310 --> 00:42:49.220
we've got the energy of
the incoming material,

00:42:49.220 --> 00:42:54.208
and now we have a mass ratio.

00:42:54.208 --> 00:42:55.750
Because in this
case, you're actually

00:42:55.750 --> 00:42:57.370
undergoing some sort
of a hard sphere

00:42:57.370 --> 00:43:02.020
collision between one
atom and the other times

00:43:02.020 --> 00:43:03.020
the natural log.

00:43:03.020 --> 00:43:06.310
This is going to look
awfully familiar.

00:43:06.310 --> 00:43:10.980
It ends up being some
energy term over--

00:43:10.980 --> 00:43:14.200
actually, let's
just go with-- yeah,

00:43:14.200 --> 00:43:18.280
gamma ei over some new energy.

00:43:18.280 --> 00:43:22.550
This thing right here is called
the displacement threshold

00:43:22.550 --> 00:43:23.050
energy.

00:43:28.120 --> 00:43:35.730
And it ranges from about 25 to
90 eV, but it's usually 40 eV.

00:43:35.730 --> 00:43:37.360
And what that is--
it's the max--

00:43:37.360 --> 00:43:39.130
the minimum amount
of energy that

00:43:39.130 --> 00:43:43.300
has to be imparted to a nucleus
smack head on in order for it

00:43:43.300 --> 00:43:46.090
to move from its
original atomic position.

00:43:46.090 --> 00:43:48.990
And that's what's known as a
hard sphere type collision.

00:43:48.990 --> 00:43:52.120
Or in this case,
it's just like all

00:43:52.120 --> 00:43:56.230
the other
q-equation-looking scenarios

00:43:56.230 --> 00:43:59.730
that we looked at before.

00:43:59.730 --> 00:44:02.770
So let's say the little
nucleus goes off,

00:44:02.770 --> 00:44:05.395
and the big nucleus goes off.

00:44:05.395 --> 00:44:07.270
This should look familiar
by now because I've

00:44:07.270 --> 00:44:09.610
harped on it probably too much.

00:44:09.610 --> 00:44:13.960
Now what I want you to
consider is this big nucleus

00:44:13.960 --> 00:44:14.950
had a position.

00:44:14.950 --> 00:44:18.570
It liked where it was, and
now it's been knocked away.

00:44:18.570 --> 00:44:21.610
What's left over is
an atomic vacancy,

00:44:21.610 --> 00:44:25.810
which is the most basic building
block of radiation damage.

00:44:25.810 --> 00:44:28.360
So sometimes it's neat
to look at the ratio of--

00:44:31.010 --> 00:44:31.570
let's see.

00:44:31.570 --> 00:44:33.280
Make sure I get
this ratio right.

00:44:33.280 --> 00:44:34.510
Ionization on top.

00:44:41.310 --> 00:44:44.970
To look and see when is
ionization versus radiation

00:44:44.970 --> 00:44:46.910
damage actually important.

00:44:46.910 --> 00:44:53.010
And the ratio scales with 2
times the mass of the nucleus

00:44:53.010 --> 00:44:59.145
over MeZ times their respective
natural log threshold things.

00:45:02.060 --> 00:45:06.450
And that's the ionization
potential and log gamma

00:45:06.450 --> 00:45:10.110
ei over ed.

00:45:10.110 --> 00:45:15.000
So what this says is
that for higher energies,

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:18.270
ionization is more important,
and for lower energies,

00:45:18.270 --> 00:45:20.610
nuclear stopping power
or radiation damage

00:45:20.610 --> 00:45:22.560
is more important.

00:45:22.560 --> 00:45:28.290
If we graph these two, let's
say, on a log e graph--

00:45:28.290 --> 00:45:30.450
and let's say we have
our nuclear stopping

00:45:30.450 --> 00:45:36.750
power in blue and our ionization
stopping power in green--

00:45:36.750 --> 00:45:40.760
we end up with curves that
look something like this.

00:45:44.483 --> 00:45:45.275
That's our nuclear.

00:45:48.140 --> 00:45:51.470
That's our electronic or ionic.

00:45:51.470 --> 00:45:55.490
So what this actually says is
if you fire high-energy neutrons

00:45:55.490 --> 00:45:58.760
or high-energy protons
into a material,

00:45:58.760 --> 00:46:02.450
it's ionization that does most
of the damage at high energies

00:46:02.450 --> 00:46:08.720
until you slow down to
around like 10 to 100 keV

00:46:08.720 --> 00:46:15.470
level, curiously very similar
to this 500 times i bar,

00:46:15.470 --> 00:46:19.430
the mean ionization potential,
at which point Rutherford

00:46:19.430 --> 00:46:21.590
scattering or hard
sphere scattering becomes

00:46:21.590 --> 00:46:23.518
the dominant mechanism.

00:46:23.518 --> 00:46:26.060
And so what this says is if we
want to draw a picture of what

00:46:26.060 --> 00:46:28.120
radiation damage looks like--

00:46:28.120 --> 00:46:32.450
let's say we had a proton that
we're firing into a material,

00:46:32.450 --> 00:46:36.450
and it hits some
atom that we're going

00:46:36.450 --> 00:46:40.550
to call the PKA or
Primary Knock-on Atom.

00:46:40.550 --> 00:46:43.270
That PKA then becomes--

00:46:43.270 --> 00:46:45.830
let's say it was nickel.

00:46:45.830 --> 00:46:48.920
It's like a nickel plus
26 ion because you've

00:46:48.920 --> 00:46:52.350
knocked the nucleus out of its
electron cloud, effectively,

00:46:52.350 --> 00:46:54.590
and it's now flying out
through the material.

00:46:54.590 --> 00:46:59.720
That proton might go off to
do more damage somewhere else,

00:46:59.720 --> 00:47:02.410
but it's not
actually the protons

00:47:02.410 --> 00:47:04.310
or the incoming particles
that do the bulk

00:47:04.310 --> 00:47:05.840
of the final radiation damage.

00:47:05.840 --> 00:47:12.830
The radiation damage is
mostly self-ion radiation.

00:47:12.830 --> 00:47:15.200
Even though it all starts
with the incoming particle,

00:47:15.200 --> 00:47:17.840
nothing would happen if the
incoming particle didn't

00:47:17.840 --> 00:47:18.860
show up.

00:47:18.860 --> 00:47:20.930
Most of the final
results of the damage

00:47:20.930 --> 00:47:24.590
are from these heavy
ion collisions.

00:47:24.590 --> 00:47:27.680
And so we actually talked
a little bit about--

00:47:27.680 --> 00:47:30.590
I think we talked about
when this ionization starts

00:47:30.590 --> 00:47:33.890
to pick up for electrons
versus heavy ions.

00:47:33.890 --> 00:47:37.273
If you think about when
electrons start to radiate away

00:47:37.273 --> 00:47:39.440
most of their energy, taking
it away from radiation,

00:47:39.440 --> 00:47:42.980
it's like 10 to 100 MeV.

00:47:42.980 --> 00:47:45.860
What would be the case for a
heavy ion, like even a proton?

00:47:50.270 --> 00:47:53.060
Well, what's the only
thing that changes

00:47:53.060 --> 00:47:58.586
when you change from an
electron to a proton here?

00:47:58.586 --> 00:48:00.297
AUDIENCE: The charge.

00:48:00.297 --> 00:48:02.630
MIKE SHORT: Well, yeah, the
charge is the opposite sign,

00:48:02.630 --> 00:48:04.200
but of equal strength.

00:48:04.200 --> 00:48:07.121
But what else in this formula?

00:48:07.121 --> 00:48:08.488
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:48:08.488 --> 00:48:09.530
MIKE SHORT: That's right.

00:48:12.180 --> 00:48:15.900
So for heavy ions, for
even things like protons,

00:48:15.900 --> 00:48:21.600
you need to go at
approximately 1,837

00:48:21.600 --> 00:48:26.160
squared more energy
than the electron.

00:48:26.160 --> 00:48:29.010
So we're talking in
the gigaelectron volt

00:48:29.010 --> 00:48:33.670
to teraelectron
volt range for ions.

00:48:33.670 --> 00:48:35.910
So this is why
Bremsstrahlung is not

00:48:35.910 --> 00:48:39.600
important for any sort
of ion interactions

00:48:39.600 --> 00:48:41.910
unless you are a
high-energy physicist

00:48:41.910 --> 00:48:44.040
and you're working in
the GeV or gigaelectron

00:48:44.040 --> 00:48:46.540
volt in the upper range.

00:48:46.540 --> 00:48:48.520
So we like to say in the
radiation damage field

00:48:48.520 --> 00:48:50.140
if you want to know
the total stopping

00:48:50.140 --> 00:48:55.230
power from all
interactions, you have

00:48:55.230 --> 00:49:00.920
to take into account
the ionizations.

00:49:04.590 --> 00:49:07.480
I'll just make that a
minus sign for the symbols.

00:49:07.480 --> 00:49:14.760
The nuclear and the radiative.

00:49:14.760 --> 00:49:16.890
For most radiation
damage processes

00:49:16.890 --> 00:49:21.660
except for high-energy electron
radiation, we neglect that.

00:49:21.660 --> 00:49:25.680
The reason is that the
radiative to ionization stopping

00:49:25.680 --> 00:49:28.140
power is pretty close to zero.

00:49:28.140 --> 00:49:33.610
It's like-- even at 10 NeV,
it's like 1 over 2,000 squared--

00:49:33.610 --> 00:49:35.845
or 1 over, I guess, 4,000,000.

00:49:35.845 --> 00:49:37.840
It doesn't matter at all.

00:49:37.840 --> 00:49:40.690
With heavier ions, it
becomes even less of an issue

00:49:40.690 --> 00:49:43.600
because you can deflect
a heavier ion less

00:49:43.600 --> 00:49:46.350
with the same Coulomb.

00:49:46.350 --> 00:49:48.510
And so what ends
up only mattering

00:49:48.510 --> 00:49:53.280
is the ionization stopping power
and the nuclear stopping power.

00:49:53.280 --> 00:49:57.540
It's this nuclear stopping
power that leads to collisions.

